<subSubSection pageId="40" pageNumber="41" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="40.[151,1436,690,967]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,690,715]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Ventral punctures distinctly large, excavate (char. 43.1). Orificial lateral sclerites with basal margin distinct. Sclerite complex within tube of penis body with pair of submedian, subapical well-separated sclerites (char. 84.1). Dorsal surface at base truncate (char. 64.1). Penis body subbasally notched in lateral view (char. 69.1).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="40" pageNumber="41" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="40.[151,1436,690,967]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,798,823]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Remarks.</emphasis>
This group was strongly supported in all analyses. It has four synapomorphies (char. 43.1, 64.1, 69.1, 84.1), three of which are on the male genitalia. This group is represented by two Palaearctic species (both occurring also on the Indian subcontinent) and one Indian species.
</paragraph>
